<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-04-20T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-04-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="311" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/2603</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-20T21:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 20, 1916, 9 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 21, 12.45 p.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3780. Delivered note to <persName corresp="#p_JGEGV1">Von
                                    Jagow</persName> 7.40 o’clock to-night. He read it and said he
                                thought it meant a break but had to consult with Chancellor who is
                                at Great Headquarters. He said that Germany could not give up
                                sinking merchant ships without notice in war zone.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>